    base:desc "SysML logical diagram describing logical components and interfaces"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance SysMLProductModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "SysML product‑level diagram detailing physical components"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance ACMEArchitectureModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "ACME architecture description defining components and connectors"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance AADLArchitectureModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "AADL architecture description specifying hardware‑software interfaces"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance MontiArcModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "MontiArc component‑connector model for the digital twin"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance MontiArcAutomatonBehaviorModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "MontiArc Automaton extension capturing behavioral state machines"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance SimulinkSimulationModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "MathWorks Simulink executable simulation derived from SysML models"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance CppImplementationCode : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Hand‑coded C++ implementation of twin components"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance JavaImplementationCode : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Hand‑coded Java implementation of twin components"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance WhiteBoxPhysicsSimulation : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "White‑box physics‑based simulation (e.g., finite element) linked to the twin"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance BlackBoxMLModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Black‑box machine‑learning model coupled with physics simulation for data‑driven behavior"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelTransformationEngine
]

instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "According to Document 1, a Digital Twin (as opposed to a digital shadow) provides active components that can send information back to the physical system, enabling bidirectional interaction. The Twin can generate control commands or actuation requests that are transmitted to the physical asset, allowing the physical object to be influenced or steered by the virtual model. No specific command formats or protocols are detailed in the provided texts."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity and validity are ensured through systematic traceability and verification of all model transformations, especially the conversion from SysML specifications to simulation models (e.g., Simulink). The reliability of the digital shadow depends on the correctness of underlying models and the applied data transformations; thus, verification methods are applied to guarantee transformation integrity. Uncertainty sources are acknowledged, and uncertainty quantification is advocated as part of the quality assurance process. Error detection and correction mechanisms are implied by the emphasis on traceability, enabling identification of inconsistencies between physical data and model predictions, and supporting corrective actions to maintain model accuracy."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The technical infrastructure mentioned includes the MQTT protocol (implemented by Mosquitto, Doc 2) and the ThingsBoard IoT platform (Doc 2), which together imply a network layer capable of publish/subscribe messaging over TCP/IP. The architecture typically follows a client‑broker model where sensors publish data to an MQTT broker (Mosquitto) and applications such as ThingsBoard subscribe to the data streams. Security considerations such as authentication are inherent to MQTT implementations, though exact mechanisms are not specified in the documents."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "Document 2 references cloud‑based technologies used for a CNC machine digital shadow, suggesting that the digital twin can be hosted on cloud platforms or edge/on‑premise servers that interface with the manufacturing floor. The deployment may involve scalable compute and storage resources provided by the cloud to accommodate large data volumes and analytics workloads, while edge deployment can reduce latency for real‑time control. Specific scalability or availability mechanisms are not detailed in the source material."
]